# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clock-tree-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In a synchronous logic circuit, the most common type of digital circuit, the clock signal is applied to all storage devices, flip-flops and latches, and causes them all to change state simultaneously, preventing race conditions.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] A clock signal is produced by an electronic oscillator called a clock generator.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The most common clock signal is in the form of a square wave with a 50% duty cycle.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Circuits using the clock signal for synchronization may become active at either the rising edge, falling edge, or, in the case of double data rate, both in the rising and in the falling edges of the clock cycle.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Most integrated circuits (ICs) of sufficient complexity use a clock signal in order to synchronize different parts of the circuit, cycling at a rate slower than the worst-case internal propagation delays.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In some cases, more than one clock cycle is required to perform a predictable action.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] As ICs become more complex, the problem of supplying accurate and synchronized clocks to all the circuits becomes increasingly difficult.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The preeminent example of such complex chips is the microprocessor, the central component of modern computers, which relies on a clock from a crystal oscillator.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The only exceptions are asynchronous circuits such as asynchronous CPUs.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] A clock signal might also be gated, that is, combined with a controlling signal that enables or disables the clock signal for a certain part of a circuit.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] This technique is often used to save power by effectively shutting down portions of a digital circuit when they are not in use, but comes at a cost of increased complexity in timing analysis.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Most modern synchronous circuits use only a "single phase clock" – in other words, all clock signals are (effectively) transmitted on a single wire.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In synchronous circuits, a "two-phase clock" refers to clock signals distributed on two wires, each with non-overlapping pulses.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Traditionally, one wire is called *phase 1* or *φ1* (phi1), the other wire carries the "phase 2" or "φ2" signal.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Because the two phases are guaranteed non-overlapping, gated latches rather than edge-triggered flip-flops can be used to store state information so long as the inputs to latches on one phase only depend on outputs from latches on the other phase.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Since a gated latch uses only four gates versus six gates for an edge-triggered flip-flop, a two-phase clock can lead to a design with a smaller overall gate count, but usually at some penalty in design difficulty and performance.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Metal oxide semiconductor (MOS) ICs typically used dual clock signals (a two-phase clock) in the 1970s.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] These were generated externally for both the Motorola 6800 and Intel 8080 microprocessors.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The next generation of microprocessors incorporated the clock generation on chip.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The 8080 uses a 2 MHz clock but the processing throughput is similar to the 1 MHz 6800.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The 8080 requires more clock cycles to execute a processor instruction.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Due to their dynamic logic, the 6800 has a minimum clock rate of 100 kHz and the 8080 has a minimum clock rate of 500 kHz.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Higher speed versions of both microprocessors were released by 1976.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The 6501 requires an external 2-phase clock generator.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The MOS Technology 6502 uses the same 2-phase logic internally, but also includes a 2-phase clock generator on-chip, so it only needs a single phase clock input, simplifying system design.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Some early integrated circuits use four-phase logic, requiring a four-phase clock input consisting of four separate, non-overlapping clock signals.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] This was particularly common among early microprocessors such as the National Semiconductor IMP-16, Texas Instruments TMS9900, and the Western Digital MCP-1600 chipset used in the DEC LSI-11.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Four-phase clocks have only rarely been used in newer CMOS processors such as the DEC WRL MultiTitan microprocessor. and in Intrinsity's Fast14 technology.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Most modern microprocessors and microcontrollers use a single-phase clock.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Many modern microcomputers use a "clock multiplier" which multiplies a lower frequency external clock to the appropriate clock rate of the microprocessor.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] This allows the CPU to operate at a much higher frequency than the rest of the computer, which affords performance gains in situations where the CPU does not need to wait on an external factor (like memory or input/output).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The vast majority of digital devices do not require a clock at a fixed, constant frequency.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] As long as the minimum and maximum clock periods are respected, the time between clock edges can vary widely from one edge to the next and back again.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Such digital devices work just as well with a clock generator that dynamically changes its frequency, such as spread-spectrum clock generation, dynamic frequency scaling, etc.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Devices that use static logic do not even have a maximum clock period (or, in other words, minimum clock frequency); such devices can be slowed and paused indefinitely, then resumed at full clock speed at any later time.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Some sensitive mixed-signal circuits, such as precision analog-to-digital converters, use sine waves rather than square waves as their clock signals, because square waves contain high-frequency harmonics that can interfere with the analog circuitry and cause noise.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Such sine wave clocks are often differential signals, because this type of signal has twice the slew rate, and therefore half the timing uncertainty, of a single-ended signal with the same voltage range.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Differential signals radiate less strongly than a single line.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Alternatively, a single line shielded by power and ground lines can be used.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In CMOS circuits, gate capacitances are charged and discharged continually.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] A capacitor does not dissipate energy, but energy is wasted in the driving transistors.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In reversible computing, inductors can be used to store this energy and reduce the energy loss, but they tend to be quite large.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Alternatively, using a sine wave clock, CMOS transmission gates and energy-saving techniques, the power requirements can be reduced.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The most effective way to get the clock signal to every part of a chip that needs it, with the lowest skew, is a metal grid.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] In a large microprocessor, the power used to drive the clock signal can be over 30% of the total power used by the entire chip.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The whole structure with the gates at the ends and all amplifiers in between have to be loaded and unloaded every cycle.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] To save energy, clock gating temporarily shuts off part of the tree.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The **clock distribution network** (or **clock tree**, when this network forms a tree such as an H-tree) distributes the clock signal(s) from a common point to all the elements that need it.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Since this function is vital to the operation of a synchronous system, much attention has been given to the characteristics of these clock signals and the electrical networks used in their distribution.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Clock signals are often regarded as simple control signals; however, these signals have some very special characteristics and attributes.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Clock signals are typically loaded with the greatest fanout and operate at the highest speeds of any signal within the synchronous system.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Since the data signals are provided with a temporal reference by the clock signals, the clock waveforms must be particularly clean and sharp.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Furthermore, these clock signals are particularly affected by technology scaling (see Moore's law), in that long global interconnect lines become significantly more resistive as line dimensions are decreased.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] This increased line resistance is one of the primary reasons for the increasing significance of clock distribution on synchronous performance.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Finally, the control of any differences and uncertainty in the arrival times of the clock signals can severely limit the maximum performance of the entire system and create race conditions in which an incorrect data signal may latch within a register.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Most synchronous digital systems consist of cascaded banks of sequential registers with combinational logic between each set of registers.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The functional requirements of the digital system are satisfied by the logic stages.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Each logic stage introduces delay that affects timing performance, and the timing performance of the digital design can be evaluated relative to the timing requirements by a timing analysis.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Often special considerations must be given in order to meet the timing requirements.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] For example, the global performance and local timing requirements may be satisfied by the careful insertion of pipeline registers into equally spaced time windows to satisfy critical worst-case timing constraints.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] A proper design of the clock distribution network helps ensure that critical timing requirements are satisfied and that no race conditions exist (see also clock skew).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] The delay components that make up a general synchronous system are composed of three individual subsystems: the memory storage elements, the logic elements, and the clocking circuitry and distribution network.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Novel structures are currently under development to ameliorate these issues and provide effective solutions.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-distribution-network] Important areas of research include resonant clocking techniques ("resonant clock mesh"), on-chip optical interconnect, and local synchronization methodologies.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] The operation of most digital circuits is synchronized by a periodic signal known as a "clock" that dictates the sequence and pacing of the devices on the circuit.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This clock is distributed from a single source to all the memory elements of the circuit, which for example could be registers or flip-flops.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In a circuit using edge-triggered registers, when the clock edge or tick arrives at a register, the register transfers the register input to the register output, and these new output values flow through combinational logic to provide the values at register inputs for the next clock tick.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Ideally, the input to each memory element reaches its final value in time for the next clock tick so that the behavior of the whole circuit can be predicted exactly.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] The maximum speed at which a system can run must account for the variance that occurs between the various elements of a circuit due to differences in physical composition, temperature, and path length.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In a synchronous circuit, two registers, or flip-flops, are said to be "sequentially adjacent" if a logic path connects them.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Given two sequentially adjacent registers R*i* and R*j* with clock arrival times at the source and destination register clock pins equal to TC*i* and TC*j* respectively, clock skew can be defined as: Tskew *i, j* = TC*i* − TC*j*.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Clock skew can be caused by many different things, such as wire-interconnect length, temperature variations, variation in intermediate devices, capacitive coupling, material imperfections, and differences in input capacitance on the clock inputs of devices using the clock.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] As the clock rate of a circuit increases, timing becomes more critical and less variation can be tolerated if the circuit is to function properly.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] There are two types of clock skew: **negative skew** and **positive skew**.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Positive skew occurs when the receiving register receives the clock tick later than the transmitting register.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Negative skew is the opposite: the transmitting register gets the clock tick later than the receiving register.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Zero clock skew refers to the arrival of the clock tick simultaneously at transmitting and receiving register.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] There are two types of violation that can be caused by clock skew.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This is called a **hold violation** because the previous data is not held long enough at the destination flip-flop to be properly clocked through.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Another problem is caused if the destination flip-flop receives the clock tick earlier than the source flip-flop - the data signal has that much less time to reach the destination flip-flop before the next clock tick.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] If it fails to do so, a **setup violation** occurs, so-called because the new data was not set up and stable before the next clock tick arrived.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] A hold violation is more serious than a setup violation because it cannot be fixed by increasing the clock period.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Positive skew and negative skew cannot negatively impact setup and hold timing constraints respectively (see inequalities below).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Where a signal broadly clocks a circuit, the signals/state-transitions it initiates must be stabilized before it signals another set of state transitions -- and that limits the clock's upper frequency.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Skew thus decreases the clock frequency at which the circuit will operate correctly.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Positive clock skews are good for fixing setup violations, but can cause hold violations.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Negative clock skew can guard against a hold violation, but can cause a setup violation.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In the above inequalities, a single parameter, *J*, is used to account for jitter.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This parameter must be an upper bound for the difference in jitter over all source register/destination register pairs.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] However, if the structure of the clock distribution network is known, different source register/destination register pairs may have different jitter parameters, and a different jitter value may be used for the hold constraint in contrast to the value for the setup constraint.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] For example, if the source register and destination register receive their clock signals from a common nearby clock buffer, the jitter bound for that hold constraint can be very small, since any variation in that clock signal will affect the two registers equally.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] For the same example, the jitter bound for the setup constraint must be larger than for the hold constraint, because jitter can vary from clock tick to clock tick.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Figures 1 and 2 illustrate a situation where intentional clock skew can benefit a synchronous circuit.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In the zero-skew circuit of figure 1, a long path goes from flip-flop FF1 to flip-flop FF2, and a short path, such as a shift-register path, from FF2 to FF3.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] The FF2 -> FF3 path is dangerously close to having a hold violation: If even a small amount of extra clock delay occurs at FF3, this could destroy the data at the D input of FF3 before the clock arrives to clock it through to FF3's Q output.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This could happen even if FF2 and FF3 were physically close to each other, if their clock inputs happened to come from different leaf buffers of a clock distribution network.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Figure 2 shows how the problem can be fixed with intentional clock skew.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] A small amount of extra delay is interposed before FF2's clock input, which then safely positions the FF2 -> FF3 path away from its hold violation.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] As an added benefit, this same extra clock delay relaxes the setup constraint for the FF1 -> FF2 path.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] The FF1 -> FF2 path can operate correctly at a clock period that is less than what is required for the zero clock skew case, by an amount equal to the delay of the added clock delay buffer.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] A common misconception about intentional clock skew is that it is necessarily more dangerous than zero clock skew, or that it requires more precise control of delays in the clock distribution network.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] However it is the zero skew circuit of figure 1 that is closer to malfunctioning - a small amount of positive clock skew for the FF2 -> FF3 pair will cause a hold violation, whereas the intentional skew circuit of figure 2 is more tolerant of unintended delay variations in clock distribution.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] If the clock arrival times at individual registers are viewed as variables to be adjusted in order to minimize the clock period while satisfying the setup and hold inequalities for all of the paths through the circuit, then the result is a Linear Programming problem.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In this linear program, zero clock skew is merely a feasible point - the solution to the linear program generally gives a clock period that is less than what is achieved by zero skew.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In addition, safety margins greater than or equal to the zero skew case can be guaranteed by setting setup and hold times and jitter bound appropriately in the linear program.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Due to the simple form of this linear program, an easily programmed algorithm is available for arriving at a solution.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Most CAD systems for VLSI and FPGA design contain facilities for optimizing clock skews.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] In addition to clock skew due to static differences in the clock latency from the clock source to each clocked register, no clock signal is perfectly periodic, so that the clock period or clock cycle time varies even at a single component, and this variation is known as clock jitter.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] At a particular point in a clock distribution network, jitter is the only contributor to the clock timing uncertainty.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Unfortunately, spatial clock skew varies in time from one cycle to the next due to local time-dependent variations in the power supply, local temperature, and noise coupling to other signals.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Thus, in the usual case of sending and receiving registers at different locations, there is no clear way to separate the total clock timing uncertainty into spatial skew and jitter.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Thus some authors use the term clock skew to describe the sum of spatial clock skew and clock jitter.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This of course means that the clock skew between two points varies from cycle to cycle, which is a complexity that is rarely mentioned.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Many other authors use the term clock skew only for the spatial variation of clock times, and use the term clock jitter to represent the rest of the total clock timing uncertainty.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] This of course means that the clock jitter must be different at each component, which again is rarely discussed.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Fortunately, in many cases, spatial clock skew remains fairly constant from cycle to cycle, so that the rest of the total clock timing uncertainty can be well approximated by a single common clock jitter value.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] On a network such as the internet, **clock skew** describes the difference in frequency (first derivative of offset with time) of different clocks within the network.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Network operations that require timestamps which are comparable across hosts can be affected by clock skew.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Network Time Protocol) have been designed to reduce clock skew, and produce more stable functions.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Some applications (such as game servers) may also use their own synchronization mechanism to avoid reliability problems due to clock skew.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Clock skew is the reason why at fast speeds or long distances, serial interfaces (e.g.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/clock-skew] Serial Attached SCSI or USB) are preferred over parallel interfaces (e.g. parallel SCSI).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] There are many methods used for delay calculation for the gate itself.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] Similarly, there are many ways to calculate the delay of a wire.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] The delay of a wire will normally be different for each destination.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] Often, it makes sense to combine the calculation of a gate and all the wires connected to its output.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] This combination is often called the *stage delay*.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] The delay of a wire or logic gate may also depend on the behaviour of the nearby components.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] This is one of the main effects that is analyzed during signal integrity checks.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] In the context of semi-custom digital design, pre-characterized digital information is often abstracted in the form of the above-mentioned 2-D look-up table (LUT).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] The idea behind the semi-custom design method is to use blocks of pre-built and tested components to build something larger, say, a chip.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] In this context, the blocks are logic gates such as NAND, OR, AND, etc.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] Although, in reality, these gates will be composed of transistors, a semi-custom engineer will only be aware of the delay information from the input pin to the output pin, called a timing arc.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] The 2D table represents the variability of the gate's delay concerning the two independent variables, usually the rate of change of the signal at the input and the load at the output pin.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] These two variables are called slew and load in design parlance.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] A static timing analysis engine will first calculate the delay of the individual cells and string them together to do further analysis.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] As chip dimensions get smaller, the delays of both gates and wires may need to be treated as statistical estimates instead of deterministic quantities.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] For gates, this requires extensions to the library formats.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] For wires, this requires methods that can calculate the means and distributions of wire delays.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/delay-calculation] In both cases, it is critical to capture the dependence on the underlying variables, such as threshold voltage and metal thickness, since these result in correlations among the delays of nearby components.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] In fractal geometry, the **H tree** is a fractal tree structure constructed from perpendicular line segments, each smaller by a factor of the square root of 2 from the next larger adjacent segment.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] It is so called because its repeating pattern resembles the letter "H".
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] It has Hausdorff dimension 2, and comes arbitrarily close to every point in a rectangle.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] Its applications include VLSI design and microwave engineering.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] An H tree can be constructed by starting with a line segment of arbitrary length, drawing two shorter segments at right angles to the first through its endpoints, and continuing in the same vein, reducing (dividing) the length of the line segments drawn at each stage by ${\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] A variant of this construction could also be defined in which the length at each iteration is multiplied by a ratio less than $1/{\sqrt {2}}$ , but for this variant the resulting shape covers only part of its bounding rectangle, with a fractal boundary.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] An alternative process that generates the same fractal set is to begin with a rectangle with sides in the ratio $1:{\sqrt {2}}$ , and repeatedly bisect it into two smaller silver rectangles, at each stage connecting the two centroids of the two smaller rectangles by a line segment.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The H tree is a self-similar fractal; its Hausdorff dimension is equal to 2.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The points of the H tree come arbitrarily close to every point in a rectangle (the same as the starting rectangle in the constructing by centroids of subdivided rectangles).
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] It follows that its topological closure is the entire rectangle.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] However, it does not include all points of the rectangle; for instance, the points on the perpendicular bisector of the initial line segment (other than the midpoint of this segment) are not included.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] In VLSI design, the H tree may be used as the layout for a complete binary tree using a total area that is proportional to the number of nodes of the tree.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] Additionally, the H tree forms a space efficient layout for trees in graph drawing, and as part of a construction of a point set for which the sum of squared edge lengths of the traveling salesman tour is large.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] It is commonly used as a clock distribution network for routing timing signals to all parts of a chip with equal propagation delays to each part, and has also been used as an interconnection network for VLSI multiprocessors.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The planar H tree can be generalized to the three-dimensional structure via adding line segments on the direction perpendicular to the H tree plane.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The resultant three-dimensional H tree has Hausdorff dimension equal to 3.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The planar H tree and its three-dimensional version have been found to constitute artificial electromagnetic atoms in photonic crystals and metamaterials and might have potential applications in microwave engineering.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] The H tree is an example of a fractal canopy, in which the angle between neighboring line segments is always 90 degrees.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] In its property of coming arbitrarily close to every point of its bounding rectangle, it also resembles a space-filling curve, although it is not itself a curve.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] Variations of the same tree structure with thickened polygonal branches in place of the line segments of the H tree have been defined by Benoit Mandelbrot, and are sometimes called the Mandelbrot tree.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/h-tree] In these variations, to avoid overlaps between the leaves of the tree and their thickened branches, the scale factor by which the size is reduced at each level must be slightly greater than ${\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] See also radio propagation, velocity factor, signal velocity and mechanical wave.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] Logic gates can have a **gate delay** ranging from picoseconds to more than 10 nanoseconds, depending on the technology being used.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] It is the time between the gate input becoming stable and the gate output becoming stable.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] Manufacturers often refer to the time from the input changing to 50% of its final input level, to the output reaching 50% of its final output level; this may depend on the direction of the level change, in which case separate fall and rise delays tPHL and tPLH or tf and tr are given.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] Reducing gate delays allows digital circuits to process data at a faster rate and improve overall performance.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] Determining the propagation delay of a combined circuit requires identifying the longest path of propagation delays from input to output, and adding each propagation delay along this path.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] The principle of logical effort utilizes propagation delays to compare designs implementing the same logical statement.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] The difference in propagation delays of logic elements is the major contributor to glitches in asynchronous circuits as a result of race conditions.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] All of these factors influence each other through an RC time constant: any increase in load capacitance increases C, heat-induced resistance the R factor, and supply threshold voltage increases will affect whether more than one time constants are required to reach the threshold.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] If the output of a logic gate is connected to a long trace or used to drive many other gates (high fanout) the propagation delay increases substantially.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] In computer networks, propagation delay is the amount of time it takes for the head of the signal to travel from the sender to the receiver.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] It can be computed as the ratio between the link length and the propagation speed over the specific medium.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] Propagation delay is equal to *d / s* where *d* is the distance and *s* is the wave propagation speed.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] In wireless communication, *s*=*c*, i.e. the speed of light.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] In copper wire, the speed *s* generally ranges from .59c to .77c.
[src:clock-tree-synthesis/propagation-delay] This delay is the major obstacle in the development of high-speed computers and is called the interconnect bottleneck in IC systems.
